We we will look at univariate statistics for two variables: Received ODA and Democratic Index

First, we will look at mean and median ODA over time

library(readxl)
AidData <- read_excel("AidData.xls")
DI <- read_excel("DI.xlsx")
options(scipen = 999)
AidData %>% gather(year, aid_received,"1960":"2018", na.rm=TRUE) -> sorted_data
sorted_data %>% 
  filter(year == 2016) -> aid2016
summarymod <-
  sorted_data %>%
    group_by(year) %>% 
    summarise(mean_aid = mean(aid_received),
              median_aid = median(aid_received),
              num = n())
summarymod %>% 
  ggplot() +
    aes(x = year , y = mean_aid) +
      geom_point()

summarymod %>% 
  ggplot() +
    aes(x = year , y = median_aid) +
      geom_point()

  ggsave("figure.png")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

Aid is steadily increasing over time. However, the last dozen data points seem to be at a similar level. Now we turn our attention to the year 2016.

aid2016 %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_histogram() +
      aes(x=`aid_received`, binwidth=0.01)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

There are clearly several data points near the 0 level. We might have to set a minimum threshold for later analysis. Overall the data is skewed left.

aid2016 %>%
  summarise(mean2016 = mean(aid_received), median2016 = median(aid_received))

Now we look at Democratic Index for the year 2016.

DI %>% 
  select(Country, Year, `Democracy index (EIU)`) -> d
colnames(d)[1] <- "Country Name"
colnames(d)[2] <- "year"
dcon <-
  d %>% 
  filter(year >2010)
dcon %>%
  filter(year == 2016) -> d16
d16 %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_histogram() +
      aes(x=`Democracy index (EIU)`) +
        labs(title = "Democratic Index - 2016", y = "Frequency", x = "Democracy")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

We can see that there are a handful of typical values. Overall the data is skewed right.

d16 %>% 
  summarise(mean2016 = mean(`Democracy index (EIU)`), median2016 = median(`Democracy index (EIU)`))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   mean2016 median2016
##      <dbl>      <dbl>

Now we merge the Aid and Democracy data to do a bivariate analysis.

options(scipen = 999)
AidData %>% gather(year, aid_received,"1960":"2018", na.rm=TRUE) -> sorted_data
sorted_data %>% 
  filter(year == 2016) -> aid2016
DI %>% 
  select(Country, Year, `Democracy index (EIU)`) -> d
colnames(d)[1] <- "Country Name"
colnames(d)[2] <- "year"
dcon <-
  d %>% 
  filter(year >2010)
dcon %>%
  filter(year == 2016) -> d16
dcon %>%
  filter(year == 2016) -> d16
a16 <- merge(d16,aid2016, by=c("Country Name","year"))
colnames(a16)[3] <- "dem"
colnames(a16)[4] <- "aid"

We try to establish the relationship betweeen Aid Received and Level of Demoracy by running a correlation test.

cor.test(x = a16$dem, y = a16$aid)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  a16$dem and a16$aid
## t = -1.4641, df = 95, p-value = 0.1465
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.33797635  0.05245536
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## -0.148544

P value greater than 0.05 suggest that the correlation is not statistically signficant.

We try to a fit a linear model to the data.

a16 %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = dem, y = aid) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(y="Aid") +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, formula = y ~ x)

model1 <- lm(formula = aid ~ dem, data = a16)
summary(model1)
